><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> gap for disadvantaged children by helping </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m develop the money management skills they will need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plan for the future from an early age</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to thrive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in life</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Vulnerable young people and those at disadvantage, including in areas of deprivation, are more likely to </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">encounter issues such as problem debt in their families and communities. The importance of financial education has been recognised in the new National </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Curriculum for England where it will feature in mathematics and citizenship at key stages 3 and 4 from 2014. Although not bound by the National Curriculum, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there is an expectation that </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academies </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and free schools </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide planned programmes of financial</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> education delivered through</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for example, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mathematics, citizenship, Personal, Social, Health and Economic education and careers guidance. In this way financial education can contribute to achievement as well as</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> developing the financial skills, knowledge a</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd confidence young people need to become effective individuals and responsible citizens. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pfeg</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> considers the latter to be as important to narrowing the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gap for disadvantaged </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pupils as </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the role </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improved attainment and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">achievement in qualifications, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">parti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cularly in term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">raising aspirations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order to do this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> effectively academies, free schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and their teachers need support, resourc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es and Continuing Professional D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evelopment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (CPD)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in financial education. Adequate channels and funding need to be in place for both initial teacher training and existing teachers to deliver high quality teaching and learning, become ‘subject’ experts and to develop leadership and management of financial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> education as part of whole school improvement. To that end</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, free schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and academy chains should engage and partner with organisations with expertise in teacher training in financial education, such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pfeg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as part of their engagement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ivil society and private organisations that can help build capacity within the education sector. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> example, a similar model to that for improving mathematics or science could be adopted for financial education using Teaching Schools and specialist provid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ers such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pfeg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pfeg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provides training and bespoke consultancy for schools (free of charge) through its ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Centres of Excellence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Schools working towards the award complete an evidence-based portfolio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> assessed against a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> set of professional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> standards and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supported by one of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pfeg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">high