nt-size:11pt">National </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nformation about schools’ abi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lity to prepare students for life after school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and narrowing the gap for disadvantaged pupils in this regard (beyond that achieved through qualifications) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">available for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prospective students and their parents/carers, and cannot be captured </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">through GCSE results alone. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If there are not going to be any accountability measures in this regard, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">pfeg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would welcome support from government to encourage academies, free schools and academy chains to make full use of their freedom from the National Curr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iculum to incorporate effective financial education in the curriculum for all young people including those who are disadvantaged.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size